  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "According to the law of inertia (Newton's First Law of Motion), an object at rest will remain at rest, and an object in motion will continue moving in a straight line at a constant velocity, unless acted upon by an external force. \n\nIn the context of the law of inertia, the magnitude of the force applied by a body on an object is zero. This is because:\n\n1. If an object is at rest, it will remain at rest with no force applied.\n2. If an object is in uniform motion, it will continue moving at the same speed and in the same direction with no force applied.\n\nThe law of inertia essentially states that an object will not change its state of motion by itself. Any change in motion requires an external force to be applied. Therefore, in the absence of external forces, the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object is zero.",
